<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-12-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="47" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d47">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72115/2612</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                President <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 7, 1916</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose herewith a
                            confidential telegram received from Mr. Grew<note n="20" xml:id="d47fn1">Telegram No. 4689, Dec. 5, 1916, from the Chargé in Germany, <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_868">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, supp., p.
                                    868</ref>.</note> in answer to our telegram of November
                                29th<note n="21" xml:id="d47fn2">
                                <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_70">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 70</ref>.</note>—which is the
                            one we took such care to prevent from becoming public.</p>
                        <pb facs="0115" n="47" xml:id="pg_47"/>
                        <p>I cannot say that I find Mr. Grew’s telegram very encouraging but I
                            suppose no judgment should be formed until the Chancellor has had an
                            opportunity to consult with Mr. Zimmermann and make a formal answer.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>